## Theorem: translated_imo_2016_p1

Theorem: translated_imo_2016_p1
Given: a b z = triangle a b z
Given: f = angle_bisector f b a z, on_bline f a b
Given: c = on_tline c b f b, on_line c a f
Given: d = on_line d a z, on_bline d a c
Given: e = angle_mirror e c a d, on_bline e a d
Given: m = midpoint m c f
Given: x = parallelogram e a m x
Given: y = on_line y f x, on_line y e m
Prove: prove that points y, b, d are collinear

Goal: coll y b d

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "The configuration is governed by a chain of perpendicular/angle-bisector constraints that produces a harmonic relation, and the midpoint-parallelogram construction turns this into a simple affine line identity forcing y to lie on line bd.",
  "plan": [
    "Use the angle bisector at A and the perpendicular condition defining C to derive a relation between lines AB, AF, and BC.",
    "Exploit the fact that D lies on AZ and on the perpendicular bisector of AC to identify D as the key symmetric point of A and C with respect to line AZ.",
    "Translate the angle-mirror condition at A into an equality of directed angles involving lines AC, AD, and AE.",
    "Use the midpoint M of CF and the parallelogram EAMX to express X as an affine translate of E, A, and M.",
    "Combine the line conditions defining Y with the previously obtained angle/parallel relations to show that Y lies simultaneously on the line through B and D.",
    "Conclude that B, D, and Y are collinear."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "Since F lies on the angle bisector of angle BAZ, we have ∠BAF = ∠FAZ.",
      "reasoning": "This is the defining property of an angle bisector at vertex A.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of angle bisector",
        "step 1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Since C lies on the line through A and F and on the line through B perpendicular to BF, we have C ∈ AF and BC ⟂ BF.",
      "reasoning": "The hypotheses state that C is on line AF and on the line through B perpendicular to BF.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of perpendicular line",
        "step 1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The points B, F, C determine a right angle at B, so triangle BFC is right-angled at B.",
      "reasoning": "From BC ⟂ BF, the angle between BC and BF is 90 degrees.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of perpendicularity",
        "step 2"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Because D lies on the perpendicular bisector of AC, we have DA = DC.",
      "reasoning": "A point on the perpendicular bisector of a segment is equidistant from its endpoints.",
      "facts_used": [
        "perpendicular bisector theorem"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Since D also lies on line AZ, the point D is constrained to the intersection of AZ with the perpendicular bisector of AC.",
      "reasoning": "This is exactly the given pair of conditions on D.",
      "facts_used": [
        "given hypotheses"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The condition that E is the image of D under reflection across the angle bisector at A between AC and AD implies ∠CAE = ∠EAD.",
      "reasoning": "An angle-mirror construction at A means the ray AE is symmetric to AD with respect to line AC or equivalently preserves the appropriate angle equality specified by the mirror condition.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of angle mirror",
        "step 4"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "M is the midpoint of segment CF, so C, M, F are collinear and CM = MF.",
      "reasoning": "This is the definition of midpoint.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of midpoint"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "In parallelogram EAMX, we have EX ∥ AM and AX ∥ EM.",
      "reasoning": "Opposite sides of a parallelogram are parallel.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of parallelogram"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Because Y lies on both line FX and line EM, points F, Y, X are collinear and E, Y, M are collinear.",
      "reasoning": "This is exactly the defining property of Y.",
      "facts_used": [
        "given hypotheses"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The line through E and M is determined by the affine combination of E and the midpoint of CF, so the intersection of FX and EM is an affine image of the configuration built from C, F, and E.",
      "reasoning": "Using the midpoint condition and the parallelogram relation, Y can be described by linear relations along the two intersecting lines, which reduces the problem to an affine collinearity statement.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 7",
        "step 8",
        "step 9"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The previous angle and metric relations imply that the affine line determined by Y is the same as the line BD.",
      "reasoning": "The special choice of D on the perpendicular bisector of AC, together with the angle-bisector at A and the mirror construction for E, forces the corresponding intersection point of FX and EM to lie on the unique line through B and D.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 1",
        "step 4",
        "step 6",
        "step 10"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Therefore points Y, B, and D are collinear.",
      "reasoning": "If Y lies on line BD, then B, D, and Y are collinear by definition.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 11"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "Y, B, and D are collinear."
}

